post_text:
Want to see something really cool right here in your backyard? Come see the Pumpkinvine Trestle on the Silver Comet Trail!
Built in 1901, the Pumpkinvine Trestle is over 750 feet long, and rises 126 feet over Pumpkinvine Creek. The trestle was restored in 1999, and opened for Silver Comet use in 2000. The Pumpkinvine Trestle is located less than a mile west of the Rambo Road Trailhead in Dallas, Georgia.
One of the most remote areas of the Silver Comet is west of the Pumpkinvine Trestle, and travels through parts of the Paulding Wildlife Management Area. The Paulding Forest is over 25,000 acres, and areas are open to the public. For more information, visit www.silvercometga.com.

post_text:
After Union forces were repelled at New Hope Church and at Pickett's Mill, Confederate forces went on the attack. On May 28, 1864, The Confederates attacked Union forces up the Powder Springs Road (modern-day Main Street in Dallas).
Fighting ensued but the Rebels were repulsed, though both sides suffered high casualties.

Sherman left the area on June 1st and moved his army back to the Western and Atlantic Railroad to resupply. The next major battle would be at Kennesaw Mountain & Kolb's Farm with Sherman leading Union forces closer and closer to Atlanta. The lasting impact of the Civil war can be felt in Paulding County and in Georgia still to this day.

post_text: The Battle of Pickett's Mill happened on May 27th, 1864. Maj. Gen. William T. Sherman on the path to Atlanta was determined to get around the entrenched Confederate army at New Hope Church by sending a flanking move against them. Gen. Oliver Howard led the flank and after a five-hour march through rugged terrain, found the Rebels entrenched near Pickett's Mill, 15 miles west of Marietta. Fighting Ensued and a total of 2,1000 total casualties were reported (1,600 Union & 500 Confederate) this battle resulted in a Confederate VIctory and would embolden Confederate Gen. Joseph Johnston to attack Sherman’s right near Dallas the next day.

Oliver Howard led the flank and after a five-hour march through rugged terrain, found the Rebels entrenched near Pickett's Mill, 15 miles west of Marietta. Fighting Ensued and a total of 2,1000 total casualties were reported (1,600 Union & 500 Confederate) this battle resulted in a Confederate VIctory and would embolden Confederate Gen. Joseph Johnston to attack Sherman’s right near Dallas the next day.

post_text: The Battle of New Hope Church was fought May 25–26, 1864, between the Union force of Maj. Gen. William T. Sherman and the Confederate Army of Tennessee under Gen. Joseph E. Johnston. The battle was a result of an attempt by Sherman to outmaneuver Johnston on the Union's march to Atlanta. The battle saw 20,000 soldiers engaged in fighting with around 2,065 casualties on both sides. Ultimately the battle was a Confederate victory, but it was short-lived as Sherman's forces would eventually pass through Paulding County and continue onward toward Atlanta.

THIS WILL BE THE ONLY LOCATION AVAILABLE FOR EARLY VOTING FOR THE JUNE 9, 2020 General Primary Election. Hours will be May 18-29, 8 AM-5 PM. June 1-5, 8 AM-7 PM. Voting will be available on Saturday, May 23, and May 30 from 9 AM-4PM.
IF YOU REQUESTED AN ABSENTEE BALLOT AND HAVE NOT TURNED IT IN YET, YOU CAN STILL VOTE IN PERSON.
Please allow plenty of time for in-person voting. Only 6 voters will be allowed inside to wait in line for processing. Social distancing will be enforced for the voters' protection as well as the election staff.
Please direct all questions to 770-443-7503, elections@paulding.gov, or by using this Facebook page.
Thank you!

post_text:
Each year the second full week of April is designated National Public Safety Telecommunicators Week. This week is set aside to recognize the men and women who work behind the headsets, the telephones and the radios to help keep our responders and our families safe. Normally this is a week filled with celebration, awards, and lots of food for the members of our agency; however, this week, due to the restrictions placed on us by the COVID-19 Pandemic, we have chosen to postpone the actual celebrations to a date in the future when access to the 911 Center is not as “locked down”.

In lieu of visits, I encourage anyone who wants to send a congratulatory message or just a hello, to send it to 911@paulding.gov.

This is a very trying time for all of us, our members have done an outstanding job, leaving their loved ones each day to come to work to help keep you, your families, our responders and our citizens safe. They are the epitome of Team Paulding and are hard at work. I am proud and honored to work with them!

Regards,
David Mumford
Director
Paulding County 911

Kemp’s executive order prohibiting the assembly of 10 or more people in close quarters, the Paulding County School District is extending the closure of all schools until April 13, 2020. To monitor the most current information regarding the COVID-19 coronavirus and the Paulding County School District, please be sure to regularly check the school district’s web site at https://tinyurl.com/PCSDcoronavirus.

March 16 at 11:06 PM ·

Sheriff Gary Gulledge attended a meeting this evening with almost every state and local elected official in Paulding County. Officials met with many of our local government leadership team members at the Paulding County Board of Commissioner’s meeting room. Officials met on where Paulding County stands in response to the COVID-19 pandemic. shared_text:
Paulding County E-9-1-1 Communications Center
March 16 at 5:24 PM ·

Here are a few tips regarding calling 911 over the next several weeks as things continue to progress with the #COVID19

Call 911 if you experience the following...
🚨 Have difficulty breathing and/or are choking
🚨 Have an allergic reaction
🚨 Have symptoms of heart attack or stroke
🚨 Are confused, disoriented, or dizzy
🚨 Have difficulty speaking, walking, or seeing
🚨 Are experiencing sudden, severe pain

DO NOT call 911 if you...
🚫 Want information about the COVID-19
🚫 Need a ride to the doctor's office
🚫 Want to get tested for the COVID-19
🚫 Have mild symptoms

#WhenToCall911ForEmergencies #PauldingE911 #PauldingEMA #CDC #DepartmentOfPublicHealth

WATER SYSTEM LOBBY CLOSED

The Paulding Water System lobby will be closed beginning March 16, 2020 until further notice due to the current health situation. Water System staff will continue to provide on-site service to customers through the drive-thru at the rear of the Customer Service Center located at 3844 Atlanta Highway, Hiram. Please consider using one of the ways to establish service or pay bills from the convenience of your home that are listed on the Water System web page at www.paulding.gov.

post_text: Congratulations to the first class of the Advanced EMT program. Their certification will go a long way in keeping the citizens of Paulding County Safe!
shared_text:
Paulding County Fire/Rescue is with Lisa Lewis and 2 others.
January 30 at 3:28 AM ·

Congratulations to our 10 firefighters who successfully competed and passed PCFD’s first-ever Advanced EMT class taught & hosted internally. This extensive program consists of more than 400 classroom, lab and clinical hours. For over 30 years our employees who have earned EMT and Paramedic certifications have attended private colleges and schools on their own time, payed tuition personally, and still worked their normal shifts. This is definitely a major milestone in the Department’s history. More importantly it helps us better provide expanded pre-hospital emergency care to the citizens of Paulding County. Congratulations to all of the new EMT’a and to our EMS Coordintor Lisa Lewis who facilitated the program!!
